<br>
Crieth sat swaying gently back and forth, lost in depths of thought, on the end of the pier in Oasis. <br>
<br>
A difficult condition for one of the Dead to be in, or so their detractors would say. &quot;Glory to the Queen and our Dark Father&quot;. &quot;The Blood of the Dead for the Teir 'Dal&quot;. Aye, the ShadowKnights of Neriak were known more for acts of unsurpassed brutality than for the constructs of their minds. <br>
<br>
Yet deep beneath the cold and soulless iron carapaces of these unholy automata, the warm flesh of some very keen intellects hid, and watched, and thought. Some minds keenly saw the ebb and flow of armies in great battles, some the great mysteries of the arcane, some could sway the thoughts of others, yet others could piece the even the most guarded of hearts. To each, the gifts of the Dark Father are different. To Crieth had come the gift of prescience. <br>
<br>
Her mind now swirled with countless myriad fragments of ideas. They danced, like the reflections of the moon on the surface of the ocean before her. Like fireflies under a mating moon, they circled madly, urgently seeking to consummate themselves and join to produce some coherent whole.  Yet such such recognition eluded her. <br>
<br>
Staring remotely into the lightening sky, she sought once more bring her thoughts into focus, and over her the visions once again flowed: <br>
<br>
    . . .the Redhand, so serenely disposed in her chambers, yet eyes mad with some earthly lust as they stared at the bundle before her. . . <br>
<br>
    . . . the Obsidian Blade, seemingly disintegrating before her eyes. . . <br>
<br>
    . . . the face of a human ranger, lips drawn back in a rictus of agony and hate as her blade defiled his manhood and eviscerated him in one easy motion . . . <br>
<br>
    . . . humans, drilling and training for battle in a secluded glade, their faces stern and grim, yet confident . . . <br>
<br>
    . . . the General, staring intently at lists in front of him, fists balled in impotent fury . . . <br>
<br>
    . . . The Statue. It's inky black finish seeming to draw all light unto itself. She could almost feel the silky smoothness of its surface. The sleek almost sensual lines of the proud beast it depicted. And above all, the almost palpable feeling of power that emanated from it. The answers to all her questions, the solution to all her problems and the satisfaction all her desires lay within that figure. It had to be hers, she had to posess it, let it posess her, feel it. She could feel it drawing her mind, her soul to it. She . . . <br>
<br>
Crieth jumped up, her eyes wide with terror, her companion blade dropping to the planks beside her. Then, trembling violently, she sank back to the deck as the first rays of the sun crested the distant horizon before her. The spell was broken, and the visions lost. <br>
<br>
The Statue. She had never seen it, never really heard of it, except as snatched fragments of conversation in passing. Yet it had seemed so real in her mind. What was it, and what power did it have over the Redhand, the Blade, her and others. Her mind, now whirring madly, sought to order these and other flashes that had come to her. <br>
<br>
There was one who could help her, perhaps infer some order from these chaotic fragments. Yet she was loath to embark on a quest to seek such knowledge, for she feared what the revelations might mean for her, and her new found companions. <br>
<br>
Visibly shaken from the nights events, Crieth packed together her things and turned her back on the warmth of the rising sun. Away to the West was the person she sought, that much her prescience told her, yet whether she should seek him out or not, now that was a choice that her gifts could not make. <br>
<br>
Yet - for now she could not make that choice. Old fears and uncertainties arose within her, drowning out the sense of purpose she had so recently found. Her mind, so recently clear, clouded again with doubt. <br>
<br>
Sighing, the deeply disturbed Caretaker of the Obsidian Blade, trudged off through the dunes. <br>
<br>
<br>
Crieth, the Caretaker of the Obsidian Blade. <br>
