<br>
It assaulted her like with a violence unmatched in her experience. Keener than a Demon claw, it pierced her very soul to the core, bleeding her spirit and sanity, and leaving her bereft of feeling, of reason and of purpose. <br>
<br>
The silence of rejection. She was an outcast, deprived of the only ones she had called friends for as long as she could remember. She was no longer the Caretaker of the Obsidian Blade, but a foolish Teir 'Dal, alone in the world, and bereft of purpose. <br>
<br>
She had rejected the visions that had came to her but days before, and the search for someone to answer their riddles, in seemingly futile allegiance to the Guild that no longer held any allegiance to her. <br>
<br>
Crieth sat alone, contemplating the bloody ruin that was once her left leg with an eerie detachment. Above her diminutive form towered a blackened mangrove, disappearing upwards like an ebon tombstone into the moist darkness that characterised the Feerott, day and night. Before her, lay the stiffening form of a Lizard man, one of a party that had dogged her hunting for hours. <br>
<br>
Around her, the forest hooted and chirped with myriad bestial conversations, yet in the blackness of her fluttering heart, only the silence of isolation registered. <br>
<br>
Only a week before, emboldened with responsibility for a cohort of Blade Apprentices in the looming conflict with the Truthbringers, her life had seemed complete. Now outcast (or so it seemed), racked by increasingle violent and apocalyptic visions, and lost, she longed for the blessed release of death. <br>
<br>
&quot;Take me now, father of lies - for no greater harm can ye do to me&quot;, she screamed. <br>
<br>
A chorus of croaks and incomprehensible gutteral commands from the undergrowth to the South, gave witness to how soon her wish would be granted. The shouts of her reptilian pursuers grew louder and bolder as the first scaly head appeared a way from her. <br>
<br>
Her mind had chance for but a brief instant of intense searing pain as an unseen blade swung from her right, severing it's fragile vessel from her Iron clad torso, and sending it skittering across the mossy forest floor. <br>
<br>
Her dead eyes stared on unseeing as the lizardmen rougly tore at her armour and belongings, like a violent lover raging to reveal her flesh, while her soul fled, back to it's birthplace. <br>
<br>
Horrifying vistas of fire and blood and pain assaulted the eyes of her soul as it returned, like a whipped dog from her corporeal form to the halls of the Dark Father of the Teir 'Dal. <br>
<br>
&quot;WHY ART THOU HERE AGAIN- THOUGH UNGRATEFUL PEON&quot; the great voice of the God boomed at Crieth. <br>
<br>
&quot;THOU ART MY TOOL, AND THOU SHALT DO MY BIDDING&quot;. She was transfixed, as the mighty visage of the God filled her dead vision, the unholy face grim with ire and contempt. <br>
<br>
&quot;I COMMANDED THEE TO SEEK FOR THE HERETIC, FOR IN THIS, THE UNBELIEVERS SHALL DO MY BIDDING. WHY HAST THOU NOT GONE TO HIM?&quot;. <br>
<br>
&quot;I could not . . I did not, I will NOT be thine or anyone elses pawn again&quot;. Crieths mind screamed at her master in impotent insubordination.<br>
<br>
&quot;Find that heretic Lokus thyself, if thou cans't, for I shall not betray my friends, my comrades, my family of the Blade&quot; she riposted, mind burning with a fierce fire of rebellion. <br>
<br>
&quot;I AM THY ONLY FRIEND, THY ONLY COMRADE, AND THY ONLY FAMILY, AND THOU ART MINE TO DO WITH AS I PLEASE. DO NOT FOOL THYSELF THAT ANYTHING IS OTHER THAN AS I DOOM IT TO BE.&quot;. Innoruuk roared, his words threatening to rip her very reason to shreds.<br>
<br>
&quot;THOU HAST BEEN MADE AS A TOOL FOR ME AND MY SPORT ALONE, WITHOUT ME - THOU WOULD'ST NOT BE&quot;. <br>
<br>
&quot;Then unmake me thou Carrion Lord, send me to the deepest pits of hell, for thou cans't torment me no more than thou hast already&quot; Crieth challenged, the last vestiges of her sanity now collapsing under the weight of the dark lords spite. <br>
<br>
&quot;THOU WILT DO MY BIDDING&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;No, thou cannot rule me any more, feed my to thy demons, punish me for eternity, but thou can'st not . . &quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;SO BE IT&quot;, the Gods voice changed to an echoing laughter that smashed her like the crashing of a storm tide on the cliffs of her psyche. <br>
<br>
&quot;WELCOME TO THY HELL - FOOL&quot; boomed the voice once again with a dreadful sense of finality. <br>
<br>
And then she was gone. <br>
<br>
Crieth sank, naked and sobbing uncontrollably to the ground as the laughter of the Innoruuk echoed through her ears. <br>
<br>
The Dragoon on the gate, unnerved by her untimely arrival stepped back, then resumed his watchful vigilance at the gates of Neriak, home of the Children of Innoruuk. <br>
<br>
